Scales and index calculation

Source: vignettes/scales.Rmd
scales.Rmd

Scales

You can calculate mean indexes from a bunch of items using add_index(). A new column is created with the average value of all selected columns for each case.

Reliability and number of items are calculated with psych::alpha() and stored as column attribute named “psych.alpha”. The reliability values are printed by tab_metrics(), see the items and alpha values in the following output.

Add a single index 


data %>%
  add_index(
    starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage"),
    newcol = "idx_advantage"
  ) %>%
  report_metrics(idx_advantage)
Index: cg_adoption_advantage_0

Reverse items

Note: You can select single variables by listing them in c(), instead of using starts_with() for multiple columns by a common prefix.


data %>%
  add_index(
    starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage"),
    newcol = "idx_advantage",
    cols.reverse = starts_with("cg_adoption_"),
  ) %>%
  report_metrics(idx_advantage)
Index: cg_adoption_advantage_0

Compare the index values by group

Note: If you don’t name the index column explicitly, it is derived from the common prefix of all selected items.

data %>%
  add_index(starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage")) %>%
  report_metrics(idx_cg_adoption_advantage_0, adopter)
Index: cg_adoption_advantage_0

Add multiple indizes 

data %>%
  add_index(starts_with("cg_adoption_")) %>%
  add_index(starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage")) %>%
  add_index(starts_with("cg_adoption_fearofuse")) %>%
  add_index(starts_with("cg_adoption_social")) %>%
  
  report_metrics(starts_with("idx_cg_adoption"))
